# Chapter 45 Victory Lap

Date: Jun 9th, 2026

## Summary
The party found themselves scattered across the crumbling interior of the Woodland Manse, a ruined scholar's estate choked with ivy and shadows. Soma had clambered up through a hole to the upper level while Brewbarry and Vukradin remained stranded below a collapsed staircase. Without warning, a swarm of stirges — vicious, mosquito-like creatures with needle-sharp proboscises — dropped from the darkened rafters and latched onto Soma, beginning to drain his blood. Brewbarry, fueled by a primal fury that swelled his body to a terrifying size, launched himself up the full eight-foot height of the ruined staircase to join the fight. He seized the creatures clinging to Soma and tore them apart with his bare hands, snapping one in half and vaporizing another with a thunderous cleaving blow.

The battle was far from over. More stirges descended from the rafters, buzzing angrily and latching onto Brewbarry in retaliation. Vukradin, still below, unleashed a torrent of magically-charged mockery that rattled one of the creatures into a fatal mistake, while Valphine and her devoted half-orc follower Prutha moved swiftly toward the hole in the floor to join their companions. Soma, still in the form of a great bear, bit one of the stirges so savagely that it exploded into a gruesome mess, then raked his claws across another that had been feasting on Brewbarry. Vukradin was ambushed from above as three more stirges dropped directly onto him, one managing to sink its proboscis in before Brewbarry systematically hunted down and exterminated the last of the pests with brutal efficiency. The DM repeatedly lamented that he had hinted the creatures were lurking overhead — "they're above you, but no, nobody wants to look up. Nobody wants to look up."

With the rafters finally silent, Valphine allowed the last few hidden stirges to drop onto her before releasing a brilliant burst of radiant light that incinerated them where they fell. Prutha, wide-eyed with religious awe, thumped his chest and proclaimed the power of the sun — then added, with characteristic half-orc bluntness, that it could apparently also kill mosquitoes. The party took a moment to catch their breath before exploring the upper levels of the manse, discovering a circular room with a cast iron bathtub fed by a hot spring pump, a luxury that had clearly not been enjoyed in a very long time. The whole encounter felt lopsided to the players — having defeated the bulk of the manse's defenders in an earlier pitched battle, they were left with "a very underleveled encounter," which the DM cheerfully chalked up to the consequences of their earlier choices.

Searching the master bedroom, Vukradin correctly deduced the location of a hidden secret door by comparing the layouts of the manse's floors. While he moved into the adjoining room, Soma — still in bear form — quietly discovered a Staff of Bird Calls hanging in the bedroom and stuffed it deep into the tangled mess of fur, hoping no one had noticed. Meanwhile, Valphine explored the manse's library, its shelves bowed and broken, and found one undamaged book titled "Elvish Idioms." When she opened it, she discovered a tiny leather packet of magical powder tucked inside — a find she quietly pocketed alongside the book.

The final unexplored room on the ground floor brought the party to an abrupt halt. The dining hall walls were covered in crude, blood-painted drawings of boars chasing stick-figured humanoids, and resting on the mantelpiece were small twig figures — one for each member of the party. Brewbarry immediately warned the group not to touch them, recalling a hard-learned lesson from the wise women of his village about cursed artifacts. Valphine, reasoning that leaving such things behind would be irresponsible, decided to destroy her own effigy from a safe distance. The moment it crumbled, the remaining figures lurched to life as twig blights and launched themselves at the party. They were dispatched quickly — Vukradin obliterated one with a lance of radiant starlight, and Valphine's light reduced the rest to splinters — but not before Vukradin pointedly noted that Valphine had triggered the very trap she had been trying to avoid. Valphine was unrepentant, insisting she had been "called by Lathander to do it," and Vukradin ultimately conceded: "you were right, Valphine."

With the manse cleared, Valphine gathered the party together and cast a spell of compelled truth, creating a magical aura that prevented deliberate lies. One by one, the party's secrets came tumbling out. Soma confessed to the Staff of Bird Calls. Valphine admitted to the Dust of Disappearance. And Brewbarry, the fearsome Uthgardt barbarian, sheepishly revealed that he had taken a soft satin bathrobe and a pair of slippers from Falcon's Lodge — because he simply liked how they felt. Prutha, ever loyal to Valphine, attempted to be evasive and quietly shuffled out of the magical zone before he could be fully questioned, though not before it was noted that he had also helped himself to a bathrobe (which, the DM clarified, had actually come from the Falcon). The party debated the ethics of their findings at length before agreeing, more or less, to return what they had taken.

Returning to Falcon's Lodge — the siege of the previous sessions now behind them, Gorthok and the anchorite force defeated — the party found the orcs split: some settled comfortably into their new roles as Falcon's employees, dressed in his livery, while others were preparing to return home to Icespire Hold. The Falcon himself was in high spirits, gushing about the bards Rimardo and Corrin, whom he called the finest act he had seen north of Neverwinter. He pressed an unsealed letter into Vukradin's hands, asking him to deliver it to the pair — a formal offer of free room and board, a generous cut of the proceeds, and excellent hunting in exchange for a regular performance at his lodge. Vukradin flatly denied ever knowing the performers. Falcon also presented the party with the promised Boots of Elvenkind as their reward for clearing the Woodland Manse. Vorga, the warchief, had clearly grown tired of the Falcon's enthusiasm and fixed the party with a pointed look, reminding them of their promise to escort her tribe home to Icespire Hold.

The two-day journey north was filled with songs, food, and the particular energy of a large orc tribe in good spirits. Upon arriving at Icepire Hold, something extraordinary happened. As Valphine spoke to Prutha about building a church and converting the other orc tribes of the mountains to the cause of Lathander, her eyes transformed — permanently — into a blinding, molten golden hue, luminescent as the midday sun. It was a divine blessing, a revelation from Lathander himself, charging her with establishing a militant arm of an existing faith dedicated to fighting aberrations and evil. The DM noted this would inevitably "cause conflict with conventional" Lathanderites, and dubbed the newly fervent Prutha a "born again Lathandrite." Inspired by the transformation, Prutha and five orcs were moved to act — and seeing their fervor, Valphine instructed them to carry Lathander's cause to the other orc tribes of the mountains. Valphine cheerfully turned to leave, while Vukradin stared after her and observed, with some alarm, that she had just sent a group of religious maniacs to convert an entire mountain range of orcs.

The party made their way to the Mountain's Toe Gold Mine, eager to collect their share of the profits from the operation they had established with the wererats. Horia, the mine's sharp-eyed manager, greeted them with a detailed ledger and a proud smile, walking them through the startup costs, worker salaries, insurance premiums, remote danger bonuses, and the substantial cut taken by the Neverwinter Commission. After all of that, the party's dividend for five days of operation came to a grand total of thirty gold pieces. Vukradin and Brewbarry exchanged a long, pained look. Horia assured them that a promising new vein was close — the superstitious dwarven miner insisted the mountain was speaking to him — and that patience would yield far greater rewards. The wererats, meanwhile, were working with conspicuous diligence, clearly still intimidated by the party's last visit, and nervously raised the question of whether they might be permitted to leave their posts to fetch their promised cheese rations without being considered deserters.

The party departed the mine with their thirty gold pieces and a growing list of ambitions. They noted that the Neverwinter Commission's cut was something that would need to be renegotiated, and Brewbarry made a quiet mental note to strongly suggest to whoever was managing the dragon's recovered hoard that a finder's fee would be the right and proper thing to offer. Vukradin lamented that despite defeating dragons, clearing manses, and owning a gold mine, he still had not made meaningful progress toward funding his music studio. As the group turned their boots toward Phandalin, there was much to discuss — a political agenda to pursue — the existing Privy Council was imposed on Harbin Wester as a fig leaf rather than a genuine democratic body, and Vukradin intended to push for direct elections of the mayor, a legal process called escheatment that Valphine had apparently researched, the still-untransformed lump of dragon's gold from Cryovain's hoard that the party refused to use, and the small matter of a holy orc army now marching through the mountains in Lathander's name. Whatever came next, it was clear that the consequences of their choices were only just beginning to unfold.

