## Scenes
### The Battle of the Collapsed Staircase
#### The party deals with a collapsed staircase and an infestation of blood-sucking stirges in the Woodland Manse.
- Soma climbs through a hole to the upper level while Brewbarry and Vukradin remain at the bottom of a collapsed staircase.
- Brewbarry recovers from being knocked prone (having been "stabbed with a bunch of stakes" when the stairs collapsed — "Whatever, toothpicks") and enters a powerful rage, assuming his giant form.
- The collapsed staircase is eight feet tall; the DM rules Brewbarry could simply rage-jump it and could even lift Vukradin up, though Vukradin waves him off: "It's okay, you can leave me. Go kill some sturges."
- Three stirges descend from the rafters and latch onto Soma, beginning to drain his blood.
- Brewbarry leaps up the eight-foot height of the collapsed stairs to join the fray.
- Brewbarry attacks the stirges clinging to Soma, successfully snapping one in half and vaporizing another with a powerful cleaving blow — described by the DM as splattering "into a thousand pieces."
- More stirges descend from the rafters, latching onto Brewbarry, who shrugs off the bite: "It tickles." His rage grants resistance to the piercing damage by default, halving 5 points to 2.
- Valphine and Prutha move toward the hole in the floor to assist their companions; Prutha cries "Blessed be the light!"
- Vukradin uses magical mockery to distract a stirge, forcing a Wisdom save; when it succeeds, he burns Silvery Barbs (DC 15) to make it re-roll, and it dies.
- Soma, in bear form, bites a stirge causing it to explode "into a thousand gruesome little pieces," then uses claws (and Primal Strike) to swipe at the remaining pests on Brewbarry.
- Vukradin is ambushed by three stirges dropping from the ceiling, taking 5 points of damage as one latches on.
- Brewbarry continues his assault, systematically exterminating the remaining stirges with precise, powerful strikes, his Cleave letting him kill two at once.
- The players note the encounter is trivially easy because they killed most of the manse's defenders in the earlier pitched battle — "We're left with a very underleveled encounter." The DM: "Yes, this is what happens when you make choices… the world does change based on your choices."

### Clearing the Rafters
#### The party finishes off the last of the stirges hiding in the upper rafters of the Woodland Manse.
- Valphine holds her area-of-effect spell, moves underneath the hidden stirges, and allows them to drop onto her before releasing a burst of radiant light to incinerate them.
- Prutha, the half-orc follower, celebrates the display of power as a divine sign, thumping his chest and proclaiming "behold the power of the sun" — taking his recent religious conversion very seriously.
- The party explores the upper balcony and a circular room containing a cast iron bathtub with clawed feet, fed by a rusty but functional iron water pump drawing from a hot spring beneath the house ("Cannonballed!").
- Vukradin marvels at the warm water — "How long has it been since I had a warm bath?"

### Secrets of the Scholar's House
#### The party searches the master bedroom and library, discovering hidden treasures and a secret passage.
- Vukradin discovers a secret door by comparing the floor plans of the manse — "compare the first and second floor maps." The DM notes "a lot of people are not capable of doing that," to which Soma replies they should be judged.
- The master bedroom contains a four-poster bed, a desk, an empty wardrobe, and a fireplace with an elegant mantelpiece; a handsome billowing cloak hangs on a hook and a clawed-foot wooden chest sits against the wall.
- Soma finds a Staff of Bird Calls hidden in the room and discreetly stows it deep in his bear fur without telling the others.
- The party debates whether the manse belongs to the Falcon or the original scholar; the DM reveals the scholar who built it studied elven ruins, had no next of kin, and the orcs had merely been planning to attack the Falcon — the Falcon only wanted the assault sabotaged.
- Valphine explores a library with a 10-foot wooden balcony, a spiral staircase, and tall bowed-and-broken bookcases. Among the moldy books she finds one undamaged volume titled "Elvish Idioms," which conceals a tiny leather packet of Dust of Disappearance.

### The Twig Blight Ambush
#### The party discovers cursed twig figures in the dining hall that animate into living blights when disturbed.
- The party enters a room whose walls are covered in crude drawings, painted in blood, of boars chasing stick-figure humanoids; a smashed dining table and six broken chairs lie heaped in the eastern half.
- They find small twig figures on the mantelpiece, each representing one of the party members — "They knew we were coming."
- Brewbarry warns the group not to touch the figures, recalling that he alone passed his Wisdom save against the similar cursed effigies the party encountered in the forest; he learned from "the wise women of his village" never to touch cursed artifacts.
- Vukradin needles Valphine for apparently missing that session: "We've learned this. Maybe you missed that session, Gary."
- Valphine, reasoning that leaving them for "some innocent to encounter" would be irresponsible, casts Sacred Flame to destroy her own twig figure from a safe distance, causing the remaining figures to animate as twig blights.
- Vukradin quickly dispatches one of the blights with Starry Wisp (radiant damage).
- Valphine releases a pulse of Word of Radiance, incinerating the remaining twig blights (4 hit points each) as they attempt to attack.
- The players acknowledge being "slightly OP for this dungeon."

### Looting and the Zone of Truth
#### After clearing the manse, Valphine uses magic to interrogate the party about items they may have taken from the premises.
- While Vukradin searches the kitchen, Prutha discreetly lifts a candelabra worth 25 gold pieces from the dining room and slips it to Valphine, whispering for her not to say anything (the DM rolling stealth to keep it from Vukradin).
- Vukradin, frustrated at being constantly outflanked, declares he wants feats for better perception — "like, see invisible or something."
- Valphine casts Zone of Truth, gathering everyone into a 15-foot radius to compel the party to reveal any items taken from the Woodland Manse or Falcon's Lodge.
- Prutha is forced to admit he took something and begins producing rocks from his pockets, being evasive (passing his Charisma save) before walking outside the 15-foot radius of the zone.
- Brewbarry admits to taking a soft satin bathrobe, slippers — and, Soma suggests, the "sample shampoos" — from the lodge: "Yes, I'm a simple shit. I like my hair to be soft."
- Soma is revealed to have taken the Staff of Bird Calls.
- Valphine admits to finding the Dust of Disappearance hidden within the Elvish Idioms book.
- It emerges Prutha also took a bathrobe — which he insists came from the Falcon, not the manse, the same source as Brewbarry's towels.
- The party debates the ethics of keeping the items versus returning them to the rightful owners; Vukradin escalates from returning items to returning "the entire building to its rightful owner."

### Return to Falcon's Lodge
#### The party returns to Falcon's Lodge to report their success at the Woodland Manse and prepare for their next journey.
- The party arrives back the next day and finds the orcs settled into their new roles, with the Falcon having dressed three orcs in livery as "employees of the year."
- Vorga greets them — "You return!" — and the Falcon eagerly asks what they can tell him.
- Valphine reports she cleared the Woodland Manse, with Vukradin coaching her to phrase it as "the glory and power of Lathander has saved" the place from "all of the heathens."
- Falcon gushes about Rimardo and Corin: "they may have been the finest act I've seen north of Neverwinter. The timing, the little placards, if I could get them on my stage two nights a 10-day, I'd charge water-deep prices, and they'd pay them gratefully." He praises "the silent guy and the tall guy, the sarcasm."
- Vukradin denies any connection to the bards: "I'd never seen those people below it before in my life. Never came to see my act, why am I going to see theirs?"
- Falcon gives Vukradin an unsealed note addressed "to the extraordinary comedy act of Rimardo and Corrin," offering free room and board, a generous cut of proceeds, and excellent hunting in exchange for performing at his tavern. Vukradin files it in his "plot items list."
- Vorga, rolling her eyes at the Falcon, reminds the party of their offer to escort her tribe back to their former quarters at Icepire Hold.
- Wade notes the party had a "clock" to get to Neverwinter, which the DM confirms they have long since blown through — though they're still going, to "a very different setup."

### The Missionary Mission at Icepire Hold
#### Upon reaching Icepire Hold, Valphine receives a divine revelation and sets a new religious movement in motion among the orcs.
- The two-day journey is filled with songs, eating, and blood; the orcs lead the party up a path that avoids the stone giants — though the party had earlier insisted on following the orcs' route rather than the leisurely path.
- Valphine speaks to Prutha, claiming a vision from Lathander and giving him new instructions to convert more orcs in the Ice Bear Mountains to Lathander's cause.
- Valphine experiences a divine vision from Lathander, and her eyes permanently transform into a blinding, molten golden hue of the midday sun (the DM sending her two new unlocked abilities privately via Discord).
- Valphine names her new order "Lathander's Searing Light," a divine arm meant to enforce Lathander's will — refined, at the DM's prompting, into a mandate to fight "aberrations and evil." Lathander embraces her concept of continuous power, wanting her to lead a militant holy order.
- The DM warns the new order will cause conflict with conventional Lathanderites.
- Inspired by Valphine's glowing transformation, five more orcs from the tribe join Prutha's holy mission — and immediately ask "where do we pillage?", reframed as a missionary crusade.
- Inspired by Valphine's transformation, Prutha and five orcs resolve to go on a missionary crusade; seeing their fervor, Valphine instructs them to convert the other orc tribes; Vukradin reacts with alarm at unleashing "religious maniacs" on the mountains.
- The party departs Icepire Hold to head back toward Phandalin via the mine.

### The Gold Mine Dividend
#### The party stops at the Mountain's Toe Gold Mine to check on operations and collect their meager first earnings.
- The party arrives and finds the wererats working with conspicuous diligence; after the intimidation of the party's last visit, they "jump to attention," promising everything is going according to plan.
- A wererat anxiously assures Valphine that "the mine is very busily working," recalling that last time she had noticed nobody working; her new golden eyes leave him "a little bit disturbed."
- Horia presents a detailed ledger covering startup costs, professional costs, back-office costs, worker insurance, salaries, food supplies, and a "remote danger bonus."
- After the Neverwinter Commission's cut — the Commission being the actual owner of the land — the party receives a disappointing dividend of only thirty gold pieces for five days of operation.
- Vukradin asks to examine the books; Valphine (and the DM) confirm the records are honest.
- Vukradin likens the whole arrangement to a Nigerian prince scam — "There's all this money in the mine, but you need to buy me a gem before."
- Horia and the lead dwarven miner explain that a major new vein is close — "it's been speaking to me, so all we gotta do is give it a little bit of time, but if we pressure it too much, it's gonna disappear" — promising they'll soon "be rolling in the cache."
- The wererats fret about leaving their posts to fetch their promised cheese (sourced from Petunia's "happy cows"), with one carefully asking whether being overwhelmed by an attack while fetching cheese would count as abandoning their posts. Brewbarry: "Do we have to spell out everything for you? Come on."
- Valphine offers to escort one wererat to town the first time to show him how to secure the cheese; Vukradin objects to "babysitting" them.
- The party notes the Neverwinter Commission's large cut as something to renegotiate — Soma likens it to "the HOA of the land."
- Brewbarry and Vukradin lament their lack of personal wealth — Vukradin no closer to funding his music studio, Brewbarry desperate for his own Falcon's Lodge bathrobe — despite owning a gold mine and an untransformed lump of dragon's gold from Cryovain's hoard they refuse to use.

## Locations
### Woodland Manse
A ruined stone manor overgrown with ivy and vines, formerly belonging to a scholar who studied elven ruins scattered throughout the woods, located roughly 10 miles from Falcon's Lodge. The scholar had no next of kin. It features a collapsed eight-foot staircase, rafters infested with stirges, a library with a 10-foot wooden balcony and bowed-and-broken bookcases, a master bedroom with a four-poster bed, a circular room with a cast iron bathtub fed by a hot spring pump, a kitchen and pantry ravaged by birds and rats, and a dining hall decorated with crude, blood-painted drawings. The party cleared it of hostile creatures and discovered several hidden items. One Talosian anchorite remained at the manse and was dealt with; Grannoc himself had died in the assault on Falcon's Lodge.

### Falcon's Lodge
A hunting lodge where the party reports their success at the Woodland Manse. The Falcon has dressed several orcs in livery as employees ("employees of the year"). Known for its comfortable amenities, including soft satin bathrobes, slippers, towels, and shampoos that Brewbarry was reluctant to return.

### Icepire Hold
The former quarters of Vorga's orc tribe, located in the mountains and reached by a path that avoids the stone giants. The party escorts the orcs here, and it becomes the site where Valphine receives her divine revelation and establishes a militant arm of Lathander's faith.

### Mountain's Toe Gold Mine
A gold mining operation staffed by wererats under the management of Horia, owned (as the land) by the Neverwinter Commission. The party collects their first share of profits — a meager thirty gold pieces after numerous expenses — and learns that a promising new vein may soon yield much greater returns.

### Phandalin
The nearby town where the party plans to return to pursue democratic reform — Vukradin wants direct elections of the mayor, the existing Privy Council being an authoritarian imposition — secure a cheese supply line for their mine workers from Petunia's "happy cows," and address the dragon's recovered hoard and the legal matter of escheatment.

## Items
### Staff of Bird Calls
A wooden staff found by Soma hidden in the master bedroom of the Woodland Manse. It allows the user to mimic the sounds of various birds. Soma discreetly stowed it deep in his bear fur without telling the others, though it was later revealed under Valphine's Zone of Truth. The party considered it "phenomenally useless" for a druid; Soma quipped he should "blow a charge just to make, like, a turkey gobble in the distance."

### Dust of Disappearance
A tiny leather packet of magical powder ("Ninja dust!") found hidden inside a hollowed-out copy of 'Elvish Idioms' in the manse's library. Its existence was revealed when Valphine admitted to finding it under the Zone of Truth.

### Elvish Idioms
A rare, undamaged book found among the ruined shelves of the manse's library. It served as a hiding place for the Dust of Disappearance, tucked inside it, and now bears a hole where the packet was concealed.

### Twig Figures
Small cursed effigies made of twigs found on the mantelpiece in the manse's dining hall, each crafted to resemble one of the adventuring party members. Outwardly indistinguishable from dried figs or wood. When Valphine destroyed her own figure with Sacred Flame, the remaining ones animated as twig blights.

### Candelabra
A decorative candelabra worth twenty-five gold pieces, scavenged from the manse's dining room by Prutha and discreetly handed to Valphine as a gift, with instructions not to mention it to the others.

### Falcon's Lodge Bathrobe
An exceptionally soft, satin-lined robe that Brewbarry took from Falcon's Lodge because he enjoys the texture — along with the slippers and sample shampoos. He was compelled to admit to taking it under Valphine's Zone of Truth, declaring he is "a simple shit" who likes his hair soft, and ultimately agreed to return it. Brewbarry remained obsessed with acquiring one of his own.

### Falcon's Note
An unsealed letter addressed "to the extraordinary comedy act of Rimardo and Corrin," written by the Falcon. It pitches them a permanent performance contract at his lodge, offering free room and board, a generous cut of proceeds, and excellent hunting. Vukradin stored it in his "plot items list."

### Horia's Ledger
A detailed financial record book maintained by Horia, documenting the gold mine's startup costs, worker salaries, insurance, food supplies, remote danger bonuses, and the Neverwinter Commission's cut. Valphine questioned Horia verbally under Zone of Truth and confirmed the ledger's contents were honestly reported.

### Lump of Dragon's Gold
A rock-like lump of gold fused together inside some kind of magical container, recovered from Cryovain's treasure room. The party refuses to use or transform it, treating it as the dragon's hoard.

## Spells
### Rage
Brewbarry tapped into a primal fury, increasing his physical prowess and allowing him to assume a giant-like stature. He used it to leap up the collapsed staircase and tear through stirges with devastating cleaving blows. Rage also granted him resistance to the stirges' piercing damage by default, halving the damage they dealt.

### Vicious Mockery
Vukradin unleashed a string of magically-charged insults at a stirge, forcing a Wisdom saving throw to erode its resolve.

### Silvery Barbs
Vukradin used this spell to magically distract the stirge after it succeeded on its saving throw, forcing it to re-roll against DC 15 and ultimately ensuring its demise.

### Bless
A divine favor cast to bolster the party's accuracy (granting a 1d4 bonus to attacks) during the chaotic fight against the stirges in the Woodland Manse.

### Bardic Inspiration
Vukradin provided musical encouragement to allies, granting them an extra d8 to help land difficult hits during the stirge encounters.

### Sacred Flame
Valphine cast this spell to destroy her own twig effigy from a safe distance, the act that triggered the remaining figures to animate as twig blights.

### Word of Radiance
Valphine emanated a brilliant burst of radiant light (a 5-foot area, forcing Constitution saves), incinerating stirges that fell from the rafters onto her, and later destroying twig blights. Prutha celebrated each use as a demonstration of the power of the sun.

### Starry Wisp
Vukradin launched a mote of radiant starlight to instantly destroy one of the animated twig blights in the dining hall.

### Zone of Truth
Valphine cast this spell, gathering the party into a 15-foot radius to create a magical aura preventing those within it from speaking deliberate lies. She used it to compel the party to confess any items taken from the Woodland Manse or Falcon's Lodge — though those who succeed on a Charisma save (as Prutha did) can still be evasive — and later to verify the honesty of Horia's mining ledger.

## NPCs
### Stirges
Vicious, mosquito-like winged monsters (two hit points each) that hide in the rafters of the Woodland Manse and attack by latching onto victims to drain their blood. The party systematically exterminated them throughout the upper levels of the manse, each one exploding in a burst of "bug juice" when killed.

### Twig Blights
Small animated plant creatures (four hit points each) that sprang to life from cursed twig effigies on the mantelpiece in the manse's dining hall. They were quickly destroyed by the party.

### Prutha
A half-orc, recently and fervently converted to the worship of Lathander, who proclaims "behold the power of the sun" and thumps his chest in typical half-orcish fashion. Fiercely loyal to Valphine, whom he views as a glorious divine figure, he has figured out that "Valphine deserves treasure" and discreetly slips her a 25-gold candelabra. He helps in combat, attempts to be evasive under Zone of Truth while producing rocks from his pockets, and is ultimately tasked with building a church and converting other orc tribes in the mountains to Lathander's cause. The DM dubbed him a "born again Lathandrite."

### Boney
A skeletal companion who methodically pretends to eat pumpkins outside the manse out of habit, despite being a ghost and skeleton with no need for food.

### Vorga
The warchief who leads her tribe. She rolls her eyes at the Falcon's enthusiasm and requests that the party escort her tribe back to Icepire Hold ("If I recall correctly, there was an offer to provide some escort up to our former quarters?"). She shows mild interest in plunder — asking "will there be plunder?" — but ultimately just wants to return home.

### Falcon
The owner of the lodge who commissioned the party to sabotage the orc assault on the Woodland Manse (he does not own the manse itself). He is a massive fan of the bards Rimardo and Corrin, calling them the finest act he has seen north of Neverwinter and praising "the silent guy and the tall guy, the sarcasm." He gives Vukradin an unsealed note to deliver to them offering a performance contract, suggesting they may be retired adventurers rather than ex-adventurers.

### Horia (Horia Stonetallow)
The dwarven manager of the Mountain's Toe Gold Mine who maintains the financial ledger and explains the high operational costs, presenting the party with their first dividend of thirty gold pieces. She reassures them: "don't worry, boss, once we get that new vein going, we'll be rolling in the cache." She had needed the party to procure a special gem before mining could proceed.

### The Dwarven Miner
A superstitious expert at finding gold veins who works at the Mountain's Toe Gold Mine and required a ritual at a "special rock" before mining. He insists the mountain must be treated with patience, that the gold "speaks" to him, and that a big new vein is coming — but warns that if they "pressure it too much, it's gonna disappear."

### The Wererats
The labor force of the Mountain's Toe Gold Mine. They are intimidated by the party — jumping to attention after the terror of the last visit — and work hard to prove their efficiency, eagerly assuring Valphine the mine is busily working. They worry about their promised cheese rations (from Petunia's happy cows) and whether they can safely leave their posts to fetch supplies without being considered deserters. One is curious whether he might touch Brewbarry's coveted bathrobe.
